WEBVTT



00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:21.568
Okay, hello and welcome to the Petty Profit Podcast, where we talk about news, culture and politics from a Christian worldview.

00:00:21.376 --> 00:00:26.912
I am your host, Joel Berry, and I am an unimportant guy who likes to talk about...

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:36.768
10 important things, hence the name, The Petty Prophet. And if you're just joining us, welcome. I'm glad you're listening. We release two episodes a week. One is a solo episode hosted by myself.

00:00:36.288 --> 00:00:46.272
And then on Thursdays, we have a group discussion between me and my two brothers, Aaron and Sam, who are really smart and fun guys, and it's always a good time.

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:49.408
So I hope you stick around. I hope you enjoy the content.

00:00:49.152 --> 00:00:54.528
And if you haven't yet don't forget to go on to itunes give us a five star review that helps immensely

00:00:54.336 --> 00:01:02.720
But either way, I'm just glad you're listening. so today, just really quick, I wanted to talk about something I ran into on Twitter the other day.

00:01:02.560 --> 00:01:06.848
Twitter is always fun. Since I started doing this petty profit thing,

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:09.344
I've had to become more active on Twitter.

00:01:09.376 --> 00:01:15.968
um against my better judgment. um twitter is generally an awful place.

00:01:15.744 --> 00:01:21.792
But once you get used to the awfulness, to the point of being able to ignore it,

00:01:21.536 --> 00:01:30.176
there is some fun interaction to be had. one area of twitter that has been an unexpected blessing to me is atheist twitter, surprisingly.

00:01:30.048 --> 00:01:33.184
And today I'll explain why a little bit.

00:01:32.992 --> 00:01:34.656
There is a common

00:01:34.656 --> 00:01:40.512
sentiment I see expressed by atheists an awful lot and it

00:01:40.384 --> 00:01:42.112
Goes something like this.

00:01:41.856 --> 00:01:44.960
Well, if I was God, I wouldn't do it that way.

00:01:45.216 --> 00:01:47.200
Therefore, God must not exist.

00:01:47.744 --> 00:01:50.464
That always makes me chuckle a little.

00:01:50.944 --> 00:01:58.944
When I read statements like that, I often find that the very observations that fill an atheist with doubt and hopelessness

00:01:58.944 --> 00:02:02.176
I actually serve to fill me with wonder and hope.

00:02:02.016 --> 00:02:05.888
That's why I say it's a blessing to follow atheists on Twitter.

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:13.024
I wouldn't recommend it for everyone of course you have to be able to refrain from getting sucked into an angry argument

00:02:13.024 --> 00:02:14.048
But one,

00:02:13.824 --> 00:02:15.936
One statement in particular

00:02:15.776 --> 00:02:21.920
stood out to me this week and I wanted to talk a little bit about it and this came from a former Southern Baptist preacher

00:02:21.824 --> 00:02:24.736
who is now an atheist author.

00:02:24.608 --> 00:02:28.288
And he tweeted something like this um this is what it said

00:02:28.288 --> 00:02:33.600
And you can kind of hear the mocking tone.

00:02:33.312 --> 00:02:41.376
um as as you hear this statement he says this monotheists believe that god created one billion trillion stars.

00:02:41.344 --> 00:02:44.736
In the parts of the universe observable with telescopes,

00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:50.464
On the earth or in space, with a maximum of around five thousand of them being visible to the naked eye.

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:55.296
Also, the inhabitants of the earth would have a pretty sky to observe at night.

00:02:55.296 --> 00:02:56.928
Now,

00:02:56.800 --> 00:03:00.576
"'I had to laugh at most of the replies, which simply said, "'It's a good thing.'

00:03:00.704 --> 00:03:05.120
Um, yes, that's what we believe.

00:03:04.928 --> 00:03:12.672
And it got me thinking, though, because I've heard similar sentiments expressed by skeptics before. So let's think about that for a minute. Let's think about that.

00:03:16.160 --> 00:03:18.976
On February 4th, 1990,

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:23.904
The Voyager 1 spacecraft finally left our solar system.

00:03:24.032 --> 00:03:27.488
It had taken Voyager almost 13 years.

00:03:27.424 --> 00:03:29.024
To get to this point.

00:03:29.184 --> 00:03:33.056
A distance of 3.7 billion miles

00:03:32.928 --> 00:03:36.352
from where she had started on a launch pad in Cape Canaveral, Florida.

00:03:36.544 --> 00:03:42.528
On this day, February 4th, 1990, at the request of American astronomer Carl Sagan,

00:03:42.464 --> 00:03:46.432
The Voyager turned its camera around one last time.

00:03:46.336 --> 00:03:49.376
To take its final photograph of Earth.

00:03:49.632 --> 00:03:54.624
What we got was what some say is the single greatest photograph ever taken.

00:03:55.296 --> 00:03:59.552
It shows a vast black canvas of space punctuated

00:03:59.328 --> 00:04:02.368
By a tiny pixel-sized blue dot.

00:04:02.176 --> 00:04:04.640
Hovering in a trace of sunlight.

00:04:04.736 --> 00:04:10.336
Sagan captured the thoughts of many a skeptic in his reaction to the photo when he said this:

00:04:10.432 --> 00:04:12.480
Our posturings.

00:04:12.704 --> 00:04:19.552
Our imagined self-importance the delusion that we have some privileged position in the universe.

00:04:19.744 --> 00:04:21.216
Are challenged.

00:04:21.216 --> 00:04:23.904
By this point of pale light.

00:04:24.512 --> 00:04:25.888
Our planet.

00:04:26.656 --> 00:04:28.672
It's a lonely speck.

00:04:28.544 --> 00:04:31.904
In the great enveloping cosmic dark.

00:04:32.672 --> 00:04:33.824
You know, our...

00:04:33.632 --> 00:04:35.040
Obscurity.

00:04:35.424 --> 00:04:37.568
In all this vastness,

00:04:37.984 --> 00:04:39.456
There is no hint.

00:04:39.520 --> 00:04:41.600
That hope will come from elsewhere.

00:04:41.632 --> 00:04:43.040
To save us.

00:04:42.816 --> 00:04:44.288
From ourselves.

00:04:44.544 --> 00:04:50.048
From back on our own planet, we look up at the vastness of space and we have some of the same thoughts.

00:04:50.016 --> 00:04:53.664
Consider the nearest star to us, besides the Sun,

00:04:53.344 --> 00:04:54.976
Proxima Centauri.

00:04:54.912 --> 00:04:59.680
If you were to pack up the family van and travel there at highway speeds,

00:04:59.712 --> 00:05:08.416
Never once stopping for gas or a snack or a bathroom break, it would take you six times longer than the age of the universe to arrive there.

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:10.528
That's our next nearest star.

00:05:10.496 --> 00:05:14.464
And there are 100 billion stars in our galaxy alone.

00:05:14.592 --> 00:05:16.704
But our galaxy isn't alone either.

00:05:17.184 --> 00:05:20.192
If you were to put a grain of sand on your finger

00:05:20.544 --> 00:05:24.096
And hold it out to the sky in front of you at arm's length

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:28.640
The portion of the sky obscured by that grain of sand

00:05:28.608 --> 00:05:31.744
Is inhabited by 10,000 galaxies.

00:05:32.768 --> 00:05:35.200
And that's just the ones that are visible to us.

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:40.576
Our current observable universe is about 92 billion light years across.

00:05:40.896 --> 00:05:44.864
Based on the expansion rate of the universe and its current age,

00:05:44.672 --> 00:05:46.176
Scientists

00:05:45.952 --> 00:05:48.544
Estimate that the actual universe

00:05:48.608 --> 00:05:53.184
Could be up to 160 sextillion times longer.

00:05:53.344 --> 00:05:57.088
than the measly 92 billion light-year bubble we can observe.

00:05:57.504 --> 00:05:58.848
Now some people,

00:05:58.944 --> 00:06:05.728
Like our former Southern Baptist preacher friend on Twitter, see those numbers and distances and sizes.

00:06:05.568 --> 00:06:09.376
And after picking up pieces of their brains off the floor like

00:06:09.568 --> 00:06:11.680
Like we all do after.

00:06:11.744 --> 00:06:13.216
Contemplating

00:06:13.312 --> 00:06:15.616
Distances and sizes like that.

00:06:15.616 --> 00:06:18.304
They come to conclusions like the one that I read.

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:22.272
where he said monotheists believe their God created all these stars

00:06:22.240 --> 00:06:29.056
Only 5,000 of them are visible to the naked eye. Also, the inhabitants of the earth would have a pretty sky to observe.

00:06:29.376 --> 00:06:31.360
Really? you you believe that?

00:06:31.616 --> 00:06:33.888
And I read that and I chuckle because

00:06:34.048 --> 00:06:35.968
That sentiment is

00:06:36.064 --> 00:06:40.544
It's so close it's it's not very far removed from what

00:06:40.704 --> 00:06:48.960
David himself said in the Psalms when he looked at the heavens and the work of God's hand, and he said, Who is man that thou thinkest of him?

00:06:48.896 --> 00:06:54.368
We are this tiny speck. As Carl Sagan said, like a...

00:06:54.016 --> 00:06:58.048
Like a mote of dust floating through infinite space.

00:06:58.144 --> 00:07:02.240
So, is it irrational for us to believe in a God who would...

00:07:02.464 --> 00:07:05.024
Create such a vast universe

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:09.632
Most of which we will never be able to fully understand or observe.

00:07:10.976 --> 00:07:14.848
Would it be irrational for God to create such a universe?

00:07:15.456 --> 00:07:18.016
It's when facing questions like these

00:07:18.016 --> 00:07:20.736
I thank God that he made me a dad.

00:07:20.544 --> 00:07:21.600
Heh.

00:07:22.688 --> 00:07:27.680
Because becoming a father has helped me understand my relationship to my creator

00:07:27.904 --> 00:07:32.032
in ways I never would have otherwise, and I'll give you one example.

00:07:31.936 --> 00:07:35.904
In the months leading up to the birth of my first born twin boys,

00:07:36.032 --> 00:07:39.200
My wife and I did something rather irrational.

00:07:39.232 --> 00:07:44.384
After going from store to store and gathering up about $100 worth of materials,

00:07:44.192 --> 00:07:54.240
We spent weeks meticulously crafting a little airplane mobile to hang above the crib. It would be the finishing touch on an airplane themed room we had built.

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:55.360
built for our babies.

00:07:55.136 --> 00:07:59.552
And we poured ourselves into this project, as I'm sure many,

00:07:59.616 --> 00:08:02.944
Parents expecting their first child can relate to.

00:08:03.648 --> 00:08:13.696
My wife lovingly crafted several stuffed airplanes and stuffed clouds, each with a different color. Each little airplane involved cutting, stuffing, and sewing several parts to cut.

00:08:13.216 --> 00:08:15.136
To create the airplane shape.

00:08:14.912 --> 00:08:20.320
My assigned job was the structure of the mobile itself, which I handmade out of wood.

00:08:20.416 --> 00:08:22.240
It was a thing of beauty.

00:08:22.336 --> 00:08:23.520
Or so I thought.

00:08:23.488 --> 00:08:26.784
Perfectly balanced, stained, and sanded to perfection.

00:08:26.592 --> 00:08:31.264
We hung it proudly from the ceiling of the room above the crib and stood back.

00:08:31.072 --> 00:08:32.160
To look.

00:08:32.352 --> 00:08:34.464
On our beautiful work.

00:08:34.528 --> 00:08:35.392
And,

00:08:35.584 --> 00:08:38.080
What an irrational waste, right?

00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:38.976
After all,

00:08:38.752 --> 00:08:41.248
A baby can only see objects up to 0:01:20.

00:08:41.216 --> 00:08:43.680
10 inches away from its own face.

00:08:43.648 --> 00:08:46.176
Our sons would never really see the mobile.

00:08:46.112 --> 00:08:52.064
They would see the faintest indication of some swirling colors overhead, but they wouldn't see the airplanes.

00:08:51.840 --> 00:08:53.600
I don't even know what airplanes are.

00:08:54.240 --> 00:08:58.656
They wouldn't notice the meticulous detail of their mother's sewing skills or

00:08:58.304 --> 00:09:02.720
I appreciate the countless hours I spent designing, sanding, and staining.

00:09:02.656 --> 00:09:06.880
They would never see or appreciate the stenciled planes and the walls.

00:09:07.072 --> 00:09:11.392
Or realized that they matched perfectly with the sheet set in their crib.

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:16.160
And somewhere back in the rational part of our brains, my wife and I knew this.

00:09:16.064 --> 00:09:17.536
But it didn't matter.

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:19.136
Of course it didn't matter.

00:09:19.040 --> 00:09:27.840
These were our children. Every square inch, every poured over detail of that room was a testament of our love for our children.

00:09:27.936 --> 00:09:31.648
That they would never notice, understand, or appreciate.

00:09:31.808 --> 00:09:36.416
It was a testament of our love of creating a beautiful thing for its own sake

00:09:36.544 --> 00:09:40.352
And the manifestation of that love filled us with joy.

00:09:40.224 --> 00:09:41.184
So

00:09:41.056 --> 00:09:46.208
When I consider the time, effort, and resource it took us to prepare the baby's room,

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:51.680
For our first warn, and then remember that God can create light with a spoken word.

00:09:51.680 --> 00:09:56.896
The idea that God would create such an infinite, vast, unknowable universe for his children

00:09:56.736 --> 00:09:58.624
On the pale blue dot.

00:09:58.720 --> 00:10:00.704
No longer feels surprising.

00:10:00.928 --> 00:10:02.752
It feels obvious.

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:05.312
I can then walk outside at night

00:10:06.016 --> 00:10:11.520
Looking at the same sky that causes an atheist to feel insignificant and hopeless.

00:10:11.584 --> 00:10:14.208
Yet when I see it, I feel nothing but peace.

00:10:14.528 --> 00:10:16.544
Comfort and love.

00:10:16.384 --> 00:10:18.592
Like a child in the arms.

00:10:18.400 --> 00:10:19.680
Of his father.

00:10:19.808 --> 00:10:21.504
Now I want more people.

00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:26.560
To feel that too when they look up at the stars not just because it's a great feeling

00:10:26.592 --> 00:10:28.576
But because it's our reality,

00:10:29.088 --> 00:10:31.936
Whether or not we fully see it, understand it,

00:10:31.840 --> 00:10:33.088
Or believe it.

00:10:34.240 --> 00:10:39.840
For the Christian God's awesome creation of the universe from nothing ex nihilo

00:10:39.840 --> 00:10:41.344
Is our story.

00:10:41.472 --> 00:10:46.976
But as Greg Kokel said in his book, The Story of Reality, it's also the atheist's story.

00:10:47.104 --> 00:10:50.304
They live in the same universe under the same God.

00:10:50.176 --> 00:10:51.296
That we do.

00:10:51.328 --> 00:10:53.248
Whether or not they choose

00:10:53.344 --> 00:10:54.560
To acknowledge it.

00:10:55.168 --> 00:10:57.440
And when I walk outside and I look,

00:10:57.312 --> 00:10:59.264
With a tiny smidgen

00:10:59.104 --> 00:11:02.944
Of our corner of the Milky Way galaxy that we can observe, and I see it.

00:11:02.720 --> 00:11:05.248
Blanketing the night sky in light.

00:11:05.088 --> 00:11:06.016
I think.

00:11:05.856 --> 00:11:07.712
Man, we have no excuse.

00:11:08.128 --> 00:11:09.568
We have no excuse.

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:13.792
That's all I have for you today. This is Joel Berry, and you are listening to 94

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:17.184
To the Petty Profit Podcast, thank you for listening.
